    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-10-22T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-10-22T21:00:00-05:00" n="124"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d124">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">751G.00/10–2352: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul at Hanoi</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SPJ1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Sturm</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Hanoi</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-10-23T10:00:00+08:00"
                            >October 23, 1952—10 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>226. Dept pass Paris, Saigon; rptd info Paris 117, Saigon 178. Prime Minister
                        <persName corresp="#p_NVT1">Tam</persName> yesterday evening in interview
                    with <persName>C. Tyler Wood</persName>, Deputy Associate Director <gloss
                        target="#t_MSA1">MSA</gloss>,<note n="1" xml:id="d124fn1">
                        <persName>Wood</persName> and <persName>Theodore Tannenwald, Jr.</persName>,
                        Assistant Director and Chief of Staff, Office of the Director for Mutual
                        Security, were on visit in Indochina.</note> expressed opinion in reply
                    direct question that <gloss target="#t_VM1">VM</gloss> rebellion can be put down
                    within two years. Asked to state his reasons for this view, <persName
                        corresp="#p_NVT1">Tam</persName> said that military cadres developed
                    painfully by General <persName corresp="#p_VNG1">Vo-Nguyen-Giap</persName> over
                    years 1946 through 1949 have been largely dissipated by successive military
                    operations and replaced only by raw recruits; he added that <gloss
                        target="#t_VM1">VM</gloss> food supply problem is becoming progressively
                    acute, suggestion that means to solve it can probably not be found. Questioned
                    with regard to Chinese <gloss target="#t_Commies1">Commie</gloss> aid to <gloss
                        target="#t_VM1">VM</gloss> as a factor tending to prolong state of war,
                        <persName corresp="#p_NVT1">Tam</persName> answered that US aid to Vietnam
                    more than outweighs whatever advantage <gloss target="#t_VM1">VM</gloss> derive
                    from Chinese <gloss target="#t_Commies1">Commie</gloss> material support.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName>Wood</persName> asked <persName corresp="#p_NVT1">Tam</persName> if
                    Vietnam wld be willing accept services of US advisers in technical and financial
                    fields. Prime Minister replied that for time being this question is delicate,
                    but that when Vietnamese independence has been more firmly established the
                    country will welcome not only US advisers, but capital as well.</p>
                <p>At dinner offered by Governor Binh last evening, <persName corresp="#p_NVT1"
                        >Tam</persName> told me that because of disastrous effect of typhoon in
                    south, especially at Phanthiet, <pb facs="0302" n="270" xml:id="pg_270"/> he was
                    obliged cancel plans fly over area of operations in northwest today in order
                    return Saigon this morning. Prime Minister brief stay in Hanoi was limited
                    principally to discussion of measures now being put in effect, with fair degree
                    of success, to lower price of rice. Although he conferred with <persName
                        corresp="#p_LJ2">Letourneau</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_NVT1"
                        >Tam</persName> did not witness any part of military operation in
                    progress.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SPJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sturm</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
